'''Kagamitsukurimake Shrine''' (かがみつくりまけじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Tawaramoto|Q1203159|qid=Q1203159|1=Tawaramoto, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Shiki District|Q1155036|qid=Q1155036|1=Shiki District, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|qid=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Shikinai Shōsha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, and its former rank was village shrine under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system#miscellaneous shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=modern shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}.

=== History ===
The founding date is unknown, but the enshrined deity Mahitsune-no-Mikoto is identified with Ame-no-Mahitotsu-no-Mikoto and regarded as a deity related to metalworking. This is said to derive from the continuity of metal casting in this Kagamitsukuri district: metal-casting groups for items such as {{ill|lt=dōtaku|Q2312868|qid=Q2312868|1=Dōtaku}} at the {{ill|lt=Karako-Kagi Site|Q11418520|qid=Q11418520|1=Karako-Kagi Site}} in the {{ill|lt=Yayoi period|Q207858|qid=Q207858|1=Yayoi period}}, later inherited by the Kagamitsukuri-be in the {{ill|lt=Kofun period|Q459939|qid=Q459939|1=Kofun period}}. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}} it was called "Koyasu-sha" and "Kasuga-sha," but after {{ill|lt=separation of Buddhism and Shinto|Q1970535|qid=Q1970535|1=Shinbutsu bunri}} the shrine name was changed in {{ill|lt=1869|Q7720|qid=Q7720|1=1869}} (Meiji 2).

